WEBVTT

00:05.464 --> 00:08.425
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:08.425 --> 00:15.015
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:15.015 --> 00:18.644
<i>- My name is John Wigger.</i>
<i>I am 28 years old.</i>

00:18.644 --> 00:20.437
One of the things
I'm actually known for

00:20.437 --> 00:23.232
is I shave stuff into my chest.

00:23.232 --> 00:24.900
<i>This one time,</i>
<i>I won a sweater contest</i>

00:24.900 --> 00:26.944
by shaving a Christmas tree
into my chest.

00:26.944 --> 00:29.154
<i>So I thought,</i>
<i>"Eh, why not win $10,000</i>

00:29.154 --> 00:30.489
and shave an anvil
into my chest?"

00:30.489 --> 00:32.032
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:32.032 --> 00:34.660
<i>- I'm Ken Hall.</i>
<i>I'm 58 years old.</i>

00:34.660 --> 00:36.495
I am very competitive.

00:36.495 --> 00:39.581
<i>I spent 20 years</i>
<i>racing bicycles.</i>

00:39.581 --> 00:40.791
This opportunity to complete
on "Forged in Fire"

00:40.791 --> 00:42.543
is another opportunity

00:42.543 --> 00:44.503
<i>to challenge myself</i>
<i>against other people.</i>

00:44.503 --> 00:46.338
<i>And if you win,</i>
<i>you get $10,000.</i>

00:46.338 --> 00:48.757
That's not a bad thing, either.

00:48.757 --> 00:52.803
<i>- My name is Tim Troyer,</i>
<i>and I'm 55 years old.</i>

00:52.803 --> 00:55.430
One really unique way
that I get to use knife-making

00:55.430 --> 00:57.474
<i>is I'm working</i>
<i>in the country of Uganda</i>

00:57.474 --> 00:59.059
with ten orphan boys,

00:59.059 --> 01:01.019
teaching them to
forge knives for a living.

01:01.019 --> 01:03.272
And that has
just been super rewarding,

01:03.272 --> 01:05.732
<i>to combine my passion</i>
<i>and my hobby</i>

01:05.732 --> 01:07.693
with actually
changing the lives of people.

01:07.693 --> 01:09.069
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:09.069 --> 01:10.153
<i>- My name is Michael Peterson.</i>

01:10.153 --> 01:11.530
I've been picking up a hammer

01:11.530 --> 01:12.948
before I could even
ride a bike.

01:12.948 --> 01:14.491
<i>Learning and just</i>
<i>going out there</i>

01:14.491 --> 01:16.118
<i>after my dad</i>
<i>would get done forging,</i>

01:16.118 --> 01:18.495
<i>and just tinker around,</i>
<i>smashing hammers.</i>

01:18.495 --> 01:20.956
23 years later,
I'm still making blades.

01:20.956 --> 01:23.083
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to the Forge.

01:23.083 --> 01:26.503
Or, at least, our "Forged
in Fire" storage facility.

01:26.503 --> 01:29.131
You're about to experience
a competition in three rounds

01:29.131 --> 01:30.674
designed to test every aspect

01:30.674 --> 01:32.175
of your bladesmithing
capabilities

01:32.175 --> 01:33.760
in front of a panel
of expert judges.

01:33.760 --> 01:35.762
Let's meet them now.

01:35.762 --> 01:38.557
Up first, two-time "Forged
in Fire" champion Ben Abbott.

01:38.557 --> 01:40.017
Next, historic weapons

01:40.017 --> 01:41.977
re-creation specialist
David Baker.

01:41.977 --> 01:44.396
And last, edged weapons
specialist Doug Marcaida.

01:44.396 --> 01:46.273
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:46.273 --> 01:48.483
There's nothing I love more
than going outside

01:48.483 --> 01:50.110
on a beautiful day like today.

01:50.110 --> 01:51.778
Unfortunately for you,

01:51.778 --> 01:54.823
that means that you'll be
forging in full sunlight,

01:54.823 --> 01:56.283
making it difficult for you

01:56.283 --> 01:58.243
to judge the temperatures
in your steel.

01:58.243 --> 02:00.912
Today, you'll be doing
some coal forging.

02:00.912 --> 02:03.290
Now, we've done
coal forges before.

02:03.290 --> 02:05.917
We've done coal forging
outdoors before.

02:05.917 --> 02:07.336
But today,
we're upping the ante.

02:07.336 --> 02:09.338
We're providing you
with the coal.

02:09.338 --> 02:12.841
We're providing you with
12 inches of 1095 steel.

02:12.841 --> 02:15.594
But what we're not
providing you with...

02:15.594 --> 02:16.803
is the forge.

02:16.803 --> 02:18.430
<i>[dramatic musical flourish]</i>

02:18.430 --> 02:20.849
- This still is
"Forged in Fire," isn't it?

02:20.849 --> 02:23.018
I mean, where's the fire
going to be?

02:23.018 --> 02:25.103
- You'll have to rummage
through our storage

02:25.103 --> 02:28.857
to source the materials that
you need to build a forge.

02:28.857 --> 02:30.484
And then, once that's made,

02:30.484 --> 02:32.361
we expect you to forge us
a signature blade

02:32.361 --> 02:33.862
in your signature style

02:33.862 --> 02:36.073
that falls within
the following parameters.

02:36.073 --> 02:39.159
<i>The length of your blade must</i>
<i>be between 9 and 12 inches.</i>

02:39.159 --> 02:40.577
<i>The overall length</i>
<i>of your weapon</i>

02:40.577 --> 02:42.329
<i>must not exceed 22 inches.</i>

02:42.329 --> 02:43.580
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:43.580 --> 02:45.207
You also do not have access

02:45.207 --> 02:48.293
to any power hammers
or hydraulic equipment.

02:48.293 --> 02:49.920
Keep in mind
in the second round,

02:49.920 --> 02:51.630
you'll be attaching handles
to those blades

02:51.630 --> 02:54.174
to turn them into
fully functional weapons

02:54.174 --> 02:56.259
that will be tested
for strength and durability

02:56.259 --> 02:58.804
in a corrugated steel stab

02:58.804 --> 03:00.597
and for edge retention
in a tarp slice.

03:00.597 --> 03:02.224
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:02.224 --> 03:03.767
Good luck, bladesmiths.

03:03.767 --> 03:06.269
Your three
and a half hours starts...

03:06.269 --> 03:07.521
now.

03:07.521 --> 03:08.605
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

03:08.605 --> 03:10.273
All right, here we go.

03:10.273 --> 03:13.652
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:13.652 --> 03:15.529
So some of the materials
are usable

03:15.529 --> 03:17.197
in this storage shed
for building a forge,

03:17.197 --> 03:18.699
and some of it is useless crap.

03:18.699 --> 03:19.991
- I mean, you just
have to figure out

03:19.991 --> 03:21.535
what kind of forge
you want to make.

03:21.535 --> 03:22.828
I mean, there's
a lot of different ways

03:22.828 --> 03:24.830
to make forges, so.
- What the hell?

03:24.830 --> 03:26.706
<i>- And so to make this coal</i>
<i>forge, I know I need a base.</i>

03:26.706 --> 03:28.708
I need something
to hold my coal,

03:28.708 --> 03:30.377
and then, I need an air source.

03:30.377 --> 03:31.670
And the first thing I see
is a bunch of bricks.

03:31.670 --> 03:33.046
I'm just going
to roll with that.

03:33.046 --> 03:35.090
I don't know
what I'm doing anyway.

03:35.090 --> 03:37.592
- Let's talk about some of the
components of the coal forge.

03:37.592 --> 03:40.595
Now, obviously,
you've got your bases.

03:40.595 --> 03:43.056
<i>- You need something</i>
<i>to set your coal on,</i>

03:43.056 --> 03:45.809
<i>an air source,</i>
<i>and then a way for that air</i>

03:45.809 --> 03:47.102
<i>to get underneath the coal.</i>

03:47.102 --> 03:48.603
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:48.603 --> 03:50.480
<i>- Base done.</i>

03:50.480 --> 03:51.898
Now I'm ready
to find that air source.

03:51.898 --> 03:53.608
<i>[groovy music]</i>

03:53.608 --> 03:55.569
<i>And I find a piece of pipe.</i>

03:55.569 --> 03:58.155
I grab the shop vac,
I bring it back.

03:58.155 --> 04:00.365
I get my vacuum set up,
I turn it on.

04:00.365 --> 04:01.575
[air whooshes]

04:01.575 --> 04:03.660
Ooh, that's way too much air.

04:03.660 --> 04:05.954
So I just start
knocking slits into that hose,

04:05.954 --> 04:08.248
<i>just to kind of</i>
<i>regulate the air.</i>

04:08.248 --> 04:10.834
I solve problems for a living,
so the problem today?

04:10.834 --> 04:12.461
They say make a forge
out of nothing.

04:12.461 --> 04:13.920
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:13.920 --> 04:16.089
I make a forge out of nothing.

04:16.089 --> 04:18.967
- I have not ever
built a forge before,

04:18.967 --> 04:20.427
<i>but being an engineer</i>
<i>by training,</i>

04:20.427 --> 04:21.928
I like to make things.

04:21.928 --> 04:24.681
And so, I feel
really good about it.

04:24.681 --> 04:27.225
<i>The things that I identify</i>
<i>and grab immediately</i>

04:27.225 --> 04:29.686
<i>is a small barrel as a stand.</i>

04:29.686 --> 04:32.647
<i>I grab a kitchen sink</i>
<i>and some piping pieces</i>

04:32.647 --> 04:34.608
<i>to build the airflow,</i>
<i>and then</i>

04:34.608 --> 04:36.610
I've got a leaf blower
that I'm going to use

04:36.610 --> 04:39.154
to force the air in
to keep the fire burning.

04:39.154 --> 04:42.532
- I'm seeing some mock-ups
for some decent forges.

04:42.532 --> 04:44.534
There's a little
structural instability,

04:44.534 --> 04:46.828
but these guys
are bladesmiths, not masons.

04:46.828 --> 04:48.789
[laughter]

04:48.789 --> 04:51.166
<i>- I'm really excited</i>
<i>about this challenge</i>

04:51.166 --> 04:54.252
because I've built forges
out of household items.

04:54.252 --> 04:58.006
I built some in Uganda out of
all kinds of pieces and parts.

04:58.006 --> 04:59.925
I grab the barbecue grill

04:59.925 --> 05:01.968
because it's already
on a stand.

05:01.968 --> 05:05.096
I can cut a hole in the bottom.
I can stick a pipe up through.

05:05.096 --> 05:08.183
- What about the extreme heat
that's being generated?

05:08.183 --> 05:10.101
Is it possible to melt out
the bottom of a forge?

05:10.101 --> 05:12.270
- Yeah, you can burn out
a forge basin,

05:12.270 --> 05:14.397
but you can also just
line it with kitty litter.

05:14.397 --> 05:16.858
- So kitty litter
is a fire retardant?

05:16.858 --> 05:19.110
- It's a clay, you know?
And it just doesn't burn.

05:19.110 --> 05:20.946
<i>- I'm going with</i>
<i>this hair dryer</i>

05:20.946 --> 05:23.573
because I can
adjust the speeds.

05:23.573 --> 05:27.118
Time to get steel in there,
and start pounding out a knife.

05:27.118 --> 05:28.578
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

05:28.578 --> 05:30.413
<i>- I'm in my zone.</i>

05:30.413 --> 05:33.291
<i>20 years of forging on</i>
<i>a coal--in a coal forge.</i>

05:33.291 --> 05:34.626
That's what I'm used to.

05:34.626 --> 05:36.545
- And look, Mike's got a--

05:36.545 --> 05:38.296
he's got a break drum,
it looks like.

05:38.296 --> 05:41.508
- Yeah, that's a very classic
homemade forge.

05:41.508 --> 05:43.593
<i>- The break drum,</i>
<i>that's going to work good</i>

05:43.593 --> 05:45.595
for a fire bucket because
you know, you've got ground,

05:45.595 --> 05:47.222
<i>you've got some decent depth.</i>

05:47.222 --> 05:48.223
It ain't going
to burn out on me.

05:48.223 --> 05:49.808
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:49.808 --> 05:52.644
- Bladesmiths, half an hour
has elapsed.

05:52.644 --> 05:54.396
That gives you
just three hours remaining

05:54.396 --> 05:56.273
to finish your blades.

05:56.273 --> 05:58.733
- I'm blown away that
these guys, in a half hour,

05:58.733 --> 06:01.486
put these together
the way they did.

06:01.486 --> 06:03.613
That's really impressive.

06:03.613 --> 06:05.407
<i>- I have this giant</i>
<i>bar stock in my hand.</i>

06:05.407 --> 06:06.867
I'm thinking, "This is going to
be challenging,"

06:06.867 --> 06:08.451
because it's so thick.
It's so heavy.

06:08.451 --> 06:10.078
Come on, baby.

06:10.078 --> 06:12.873
<i>So I cut it off,</i>
<i>get it in the fire.</i>

06:12.873 --> 06:14.416
Let's just get it hot
and try to work it down.

06:14.416 --> 06:16.042
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:16.042 --> 06:17.711
<i>- As I look at</i>
<i>this piece of steel</i>

06:17.711 --> 06:19.921
and start to hammer on it,
it becomes apparent

06:19.921 --> 06:23.008
very quickly that it's going
to be just an enormous task

06:23.008 --> 06:25.677
<i>to shape and form this blade.</i>

06:25.677 --> 06:27.762
<i>I begin to think of</i>
<i>how to reduce</i>

06:27.762 --> 06:29.431
this piece of steel,

06:29.431 --> 06:32.142
and I ran over
and grabbed the angle grinder,

06:32.142 --> 06:35.186
<i>and I started trying to cut</i>
<i>this piece of steel in half.</i>

06:35.186 --> 06:36.855
<i>But I realized</i>
<i>it was going to be</i>

06:36.855 --> 06:38.899
<i>a very long, tedious process.</i>

06:38.899 --> 06:41.776
So I gave up on that approach
very quickly.

06:41.776 --> 06:45.655
- Just having to hand hammer
in this sun,

06:45.655 --> 06:47.324
in this outdoor environment,

06:47.324 --> 06:49.451
is taking its toll
on each one of them.

06:49.451 --> 06:51.453
<i>[tense music]</i>

06:51.453 --> 06:52.996
<i>- They didn't give us</i>
<i>a power hammer,</i>

06:52.996 --> 06:55.540
but luckily, I brought
my own power hammer.

06:55.540 --> 06:57.208
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:57.208 --> 06:58.585
<i>So I'm hammering</i>
<i>on this piece of metal.</i>

06:58.585 --> 07:00.378
I'm giving it everything I got.

07:00.378 --> 07:02.172
But it's not moving.

07:02.172 --> 07:04.549
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

07:04.549 --> 07:06.176
- It's just so frustrating

07:06.176 --> 07:08.261
when you hit something
and nothing happens.

07:08.261 --> 07:10.972
<i>- I'm exhausted, I'm thinking,</i>
<i>"How am I going to hammer</i>

07:10.972 --> 07:12.849
<i>this big piece of steel out?"</i>

07:12.849 --> 07:14.351
I know I have to do
something different.

07:14.351 --> 07:15.435
I'm going to have to
make this piece of metal

07:15.435 --> 07:16.936
a little bit smaller.

07:16.936 --> 07:18.313
- That metal's
going to heat up quicker.

07:18.313 --> 07:19.814
It's going to
be faster to move.

07:19.814 --> 07:21.524
<i>- So I'm using</i>
<i>the angle grinder</i>

07:21.524 --> 07:24.402
to cut a giant slash
in both sides of my steel,

07:24.402 --> 07:26.571
and use a chisel,
and split it open.

07:26.571 --> 07:29.157
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

07:29.157 --> 07:31.284
<i>- So I'm forging there.</i>
<i>I'm going to smack it.</i>

07:31.284 --> 07:32.744
Damn it.

07:32.744 --> 07:34.537
And there it goes,
on the ground.

07:34.537 --> 07:36.289
Pick it up,
throw it back in the fire,

07:36.289 --> 07:38.375
<i>heat it back up,</i>
<i>bring it over, start pounding.</i>

07:38.375 --> 07:39.668
It goes off again.

07:39.668 --> 07:42.170
This is just stupid.

07:42.170 --> 07:43.713
<i>We got to cut it down,</i>
<i>let's go.</i>

07:43.713 --> 07:45.632
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:45.632 --> 07:48.134
What I wouldn't do for
a settling torch right now.

07:48.134 --> 07:49.344
Yeah!

07:49.344 --> 07:50.929
Now the metal is thinner.

07:50.929 --> 07:52.347
<i>I'm thinking,</i>
<i>"Okay, we're going to do</i>

07:52.347 --> 07:54.391
<i>a small, Bowie-type shape."</i>

07:54.391 --> 07:57.102
A really cool-looking blade,
and pretty tough.

07:57.102 --> 08:00.313
- Whoo, God, this heat
is getting to me.

08:00.313 --> 08:01.356
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

08:01.356 --> 08:03.108
- Every single one of them

08:03.108 --> 08:06.569
has gone to the grinder
to shave a thinner billet

08:06.569 --> 08:08.613
with the exception of Ken.

08:08.613 --> 08:09.948
- Ken's steel
is all over his anvil,

08:09.948 --> 08:11.741
and he's starting
to get frustrated

08:11.741 --> 08:15.203
that he can't just take spurs
to the thing and move it.

08:15.203 --> 08:18.581
- Today, between
the temperature outside,

08:18.581 --> 08:20.166
and the piece of steel,
trying to move it.

08:20.166 --> 08:22.168
<i>I am struggling.</i>

08:22.168 --> 08:24.838
- Bladesmiths, you have
just 90 minutes remaining

08:24.838 --> 08:25.880
to finish your work.

08:25.880 --> 08:27.048
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

08:27.048 --> 08:28.550
- There we go.

08:28.550 --> 08:30.301
So I finally
get a piece cut off,

08:30.301 --> 08:32.053
<i>and it's a little bit short,</i>
<i>but I thought,</i>

08:32.053 --> 08:33.430
<i>"I can get this in the fire,</i>

08:33.430 --> 08:35.598
and I can draw this out
no problem."

08:35.598 --> 08:37.434
- The problem with a coal forge

08:37.434 --> 08:39.227
is you can get beyond
welding temperature,

08:39.227 --> 08:41.020
and actually get to the point
of burning the steel.

08:41.020 --> 08:42.772
And when you burn the steel,

08:42.772 --> 08:45.150
it gets in and ruins
the crystalline structure.

08:45.150 --> 08:46.901
<i>Once you burn it,</i>
<i>you cut it off</i>

08:46.901 --> 08:48.570
<i>and work with something</i>
<i>that hasn't burned.</i>

08:48.570 --> 08:50.822
<i>There's no coming back</i>
<i>from it.</i>

08:50.822 --> 08:52.490
- Oh.

08:52.490 --> 08:54.159
The heat's getting to me,
and I kind of just

08:54.159 --> 08:56.911
had to step aside for a second.

08:56.911 --> 08:58.538
And then, I look back over
and I went, "Oh, crap."

08:58.538 --> 09:00.665
<i>[tense music]</i>

09:00.665 --> 09:02.542
I left my blade in the forge.
I got to get back over there.

09:02.542 --> 09:04.335
Crap, now she's probably hot.

09:04.335 --> 09:08.298
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:08.298 --> 09:09.507
- Did he burn it?

09:09.507 --> 09:11.301
- Yep.
- He burnt it.

09:11.301 --> 09:13.428
- That's not good.

09:13.428 --> 09:15.805
You know, on the back of the
spine of the blade, it's burnt.

09:15.805 --> 09:17.599
<i>A big old chunk burned out.</i>

09:17.599 --> 09:19.434
That's not good at all.

09:19.434 --> 09:22.103
Could I have enough time
to split that one

09:22.103 --> 09:23.438
in the amount of time
I got left,

09:23.438 --> 09:25.190
put it together
and forge-weld it?

09:25.190 --> 09:27.984
I don't; so I'm going to
try and fix this one.

09:27.984 --> 09:29.861
- Go with what you got.

09:29.861 --> 09:31.404
- [exhales]

09:31.404 --> 09:32.989
I'm still trying
to keep positive.

09:32.989 --> 09:36.242
<i>Keep going.</i>
<i>I just can't give up.</i>

09:36.242 --> 09:38.203
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:38.203 --> 09:40.622
- My physical
and mental strengthness

09:40.622 --> 09:41.873
is really getting tested.

09:41.873 --> 09:44.167
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:44.167 --> 09:45.835
I don't want to
swing a hammer anymore.

09:45.835 --> 09:47.629
Where's Big Blue at?

09:47.629 --> 09:48.880
- He's standing
right next to you.

09:48.880 --> 09:50.423
[laughter]

09:50.423 --> 09:52.592
- He's still going!
- There you go.

09:52.592 --> 09:55.428
- The forge is hot.
The sun is beating down.

09:55.428 --> 09:57.388
It's bright,
it's hard to tell the color.

09:57.388 --> 10:00.683
<i>I start smacking it</i>
<i>like it owes me money,</i>

10:00.683 --> 10:04.145
but I'm feeling really
overheated, kind of shaky.

10:04.145 --> 10:05.730
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:05.730 --> 10:07.023
I got to take five.

10:07.023 --> 10:08.358
- There he goes,
taking a break.

10:08.358 --> 10:10.860
This is brutal.
- Yeah, it is.

10:10.860 --> 10:12.237
<i>- The risk of taking a break</i>

10:12.237 --> 10:14.364
<i>is it takes time</i>
<i>off the clock.</i>

10:14.364 --> 10:15.907
But the greater risk
is passing out,

10:15.907 --> 10:18.034
and being eliminated
altogether.

10:18.034 --> 10:19.869
- I hope that whole
piece of steel

10:19.869 --> 10:21.788
hasn't been in that forge
this whole time.

10:21.788 --> 10:24.249
<i>[tense music]</i>

10:24.249 --> 10:27.252
- Oh, geez, no.
- Oh no, no, no, no, no.

10:27.252 --> 10:29.838
- Oh, no, man.
- No, no, no, Tim, no, no.

10:29.838 --> 10:31.965
Tim burnt the tip
of his steel off.

10:31.965 --> 10:34.717
<i>- I'm hot; I'm dizzy.</i>

10:34.717 --> 10:36.511
<i>I'm looking</i>
<i>at this piece of steel.</i>

10:36.511 --> 10:39.639
Halfway about to cry,
it's just too short.

10:39.639 --> 10:41.933
<i>And it's decision time.</i>
- Oh, man.

10:41.933 --> 10:43.852
- Do I tap out,
or do I try to figure out

10:43.852 --> 10:45.979
something else and keep going?

10:45.979 --> 10:48.690
- He's back to his other piece,
which is quite a bit thicker.

10:48.690 --> 10:50.942
- This is a disaster for Tim.

10:50.942 --> 10:52.485
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:52.485 --> 10:54.362
This, by far,
has been one of our

10:54.362 --> 10:56.656
toughest challenges to date.

10:56.656 --> 10:59.617
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

10:59.617 --> 11:06.833
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:06.833 --> 11:10.962
- It looks like Ken, he's just
been hammering continuously.

11:10.962 --> 11:13.673
- But it's not moving.
All that energy.

11:13.673 --> 11:15.383
- I'm feeling for him.

11:15.383 --> 11:17.760
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:17.760 --> 11:19.554
- I'm not a novice
at making knives.

11:19.554 --> 11:21.472
I have made knives
for ten years.

11:21.472 --> 11:23.183
<i>But I've never worked with</i>
<i>a piece of steel</i>

11:23.183 --> 11:25.310
<i>this big by hand.</i>

11:25.310 --> 11:27.437
I just see I've got
so much steel to move yet

11:27.437 --> 11:29.230
to even get to a knife shape.

11:29.230 --> 11:31.941
<i>Even if I had more time,</i>
<i>I would not be able</i>

11:31.941 --> 11:34.569
to achieve the results that
I need to even submit a knife.

11:34.569 --> 11:37.155
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:37.155 --> 11:39.866
- Uh, why is Ken not moving?
- Why is Ken not moving?

11:39.866 --> 11:42.160
<i>- Time is running out.</i>

11:42.160 --> 11:44.412
I'm hot.
My pulse is racing.

11:44.412 --> 11:46.456
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:46.456 --> 11:48.333
<i>I just don't think</i>
<i>I can make it through this.</i>

11:48.333 --> 11:49.386
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:54.631 --> 11:56.424
- Uh, why is Ken not moving?
- I think he quit.

11:56.424 --> 11:57.717
- Why is Ken not moving?

11:57.717 --> 12:00.845
- I'm hot.
My pulse is racing.

12:00.845 --> 12:02.722
Time is running out.

12:02.722 --> 12:05.016
I just don't think
I can make it through this.

12:05.016 --> 12:06.893
<i>It's time to</i>
<i>throw in the towel.</i>

12:06.893 --> 12:08.937
- What's going on?
- I'm done.

12:08.937 --> 12:10.897
- You're done?
- I can't do it anymore.

12:10.897 --> 12:12.982
- You realize $10,000
and the title

12:12.982 --> 12:14.525
of "Forged in Fire" champion
is on the line?

12:14.525 --> 12:17.111
- I got a splitting headache.
I feel nauseated.

12:17.111 --> 12:19.280
- All right, sir.

12:19.280 --> 12:22.450
<i>- There's times in anybody's</i>
<i>level of competition</i>

12:22.450 --> 12:24.619
that you reach a point
where you just can't continue.

12:24.619 --> 12:27.455
<i>It was just beyond what</i>
<i>I could physically handle.</i>

12:27.455 --> 12:29.374
<i>[tense music]</i>

12:29.374 --> 12:31.042
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

12:31.042 --> 12:33.419
- We still have three smiths
that are working.

12:33.419 --> 12:36.464
The fact that Ken
has left the competition

12:36.464 --> 12:38.633
has no bearing on whether or
not these guys move forward.

12:38.633 --> 12:40.468
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:40.468 --> 12:42.595
- Tim is finally
moving some metal.

12:42.595 --> 12:46.140
<i>- Now that I got to start</i>
<i>over, I focus on the tip.</i>

12:46.140 --> 12:49.060
And then, what I worry about
is just making sure

12:49.060 --> 12:51.771
<i>that I get to parameters.</i>
- There's a knife.

12:51.771 --> 12:53.856
<i>- I keep heating up my metal,</i>
<i>I'm pulling it out,</i>

12:53.856 --> 12:55.441
<i>and I just want</i>
<i>to work on it more,</i>

12:55.441 --> 12:56.567
but there's not enough time.

12:56.567 --> 12:58.778
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

12:58.778 --> 13:00.488
- Quench.

13:00.488 --> 13:03.741
- I got a hard blade.
It looks straight enough.

13:03.741 --> 13:06.244
<i>So now, I'm going to be</i>
<i>belly up at this grinder</i>

13:06.244 --> 13:07.912
to make this blade
the best blade I can make.

13:07.912 --> 13:09.831
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:09.831 --> 13:13.084
- Bladesmiths, five minutes.
Five minutes remaining.

13:13.084 --> 13:14.836
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

13:14.836 --> 13:17.130
- Oh, we got a quench.
- There we go.

13:17.130 --> 13:18.047
- Mike's in the quench.

13:18.047 --> 13:19.173
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:19.173 --> 13:21.301
- Wow.
Whoo!

13:21.301 --> 13:24.429
I've got it hardened.
I'm feeling pretty stoked.

13:24.429 --> 13:26.347
<i>Even though</i>
<i>I'm completely wore out.</i>

13:26.347 --> 13:29.475
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:29.475 --> 13:31.269
- There you go. All right.

13:31.269 --> 13:33.187
Ooh!

13:33.187 --> 13:34.731
- So I pulled it out of the
quench, put it in a vice,

13:34.731 --> 13:36.441
<i>took a file</i>
<i>and went against it.</i>

13:36.441 --> 13:39.527
Ooh, hard, but didn't
feel hard enough.

13:39.527 --> 13:41.612
<i>And I've got to do it</i>
<i>one more time.</i>

13:41.612 --> 13:43.906
- What?
No, no.

13:43.906 --> 13:45.867
<i>- Of course I'm going</i>
<i>to have to do it twice,</i>

13:45.867 --> 13:47.577
because that's how
this whole day has gone.

13:47.577 --> 13:49.328
- This is such a risk.

13:49.328 --> 13:51.581
He's putting more and more
stress on that edge.

13:51.581 --> 13:52.665
- 30 seconds!

13:52.665 --> 13:54.625
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:54.625 --> 13:57.128
- Keep it in, keep it in,
keep it in, keep it in, in.

13:57.128 --> 13:59.255
There you go.

13:59.255 --> 14:02.133
<i>- Pull it out,</i>
<i>it looks pretty straight.</i>

14:02.133 --> 14:03.551
- That'll work.

14:03.551 --> 14:09.057
- Five, four, three, two, one.

14:09.057 --> 14:11.100
Bladesmiths,
shut down your machines.

14:11.100 --> 14:13.227
Drop your tools.
- Oh-ho-ho.

14:13.227 --> 14:15.354
- This round of competition
is over.

14:15.354 --> 14:16.773
- Whoo.
- Nice.

14:16.773 --> 14:19.067
<i>[tense music]</i>

14:19.067 --> 14:20.735
<i>- The blade, it's ugly.</i>

14:20.735 --> 14:24.072
But, uh--I believe
I'm going to make it work.

14:24.072 --> 14:26.282
- Bladesmiths,
that was a tough first round,

14:26.282 --> 14:27.700
and intentionally so.

14:27.700 --> 14:29.202
We're always pushing the limits

14:29.202 --> 14:31.621
of what's possible
in weaponsmithing.

14:31.621 --> 14:33.081
One of your competitors

14:33.081 --> 14:35.625
self-eliminated
from this competition.

14:35.625 --> 14:37.835
Your blades still need
to make the parameters.

14:37.835 --> 14:39.712
Michael, you're up first.

14:39.712 --> 14:41.756
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:41.756 --> 14:44.926
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

14:44.926 --> 14:48.304
<i>- Your steel looks solid,</i>
<i>for the most part.</i>

14:48.304 --> 14:50.389
You've got it kind of
necked in right here,

14:50.389 --> 14:53.601
and there's a bit of an issue
on the edge side.

14:53.601 --> 14:55.103
<i>You can see that</i>
<i>there's a crack</i>

14:55.103 --> 14:56.646
<i>that works its way</i>
<i>back in there.</i>

14:56.646 --> 14:58.356
But you left enough mass

14:58.356 --> 15:00.066
in this blade
to get around that, so good.

15:00.066 --> 15:01.943
- Thank you.
- All right, Tim.

15:01.943 --> 15:03.611
Please present
your blade to the judges.

15:03.611 --> 15:06.197
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:06.197 --> 15:08.241
<i>- It's obviously</i>
<i>a very rough knife.</i>

15:08.241 --> 15:09.784
I'd like to see a lot
of this mass taken away,

15:09.784 --> 15:11.202
and an edge put on it.

15:11.202 --> 15:12.995
I would really
address this tang.

15:12.995 --> 15:15.039
It's a weak spot back here.
There's some cracking

15:15.039 --> 15:17.208
<i>and some fissures going on</i>
<i>that need to be addressed.</i>

15:17.208 --> 15:19.877
But in all, it's just--
it's a solid knife.

15:19.877 --> 15:21.629
So, well done.
- Thank you.

15:21.629 --> 15:23.589
- All right, steady pace John.

15:23.589 --> 15:25.508
Please present your steel
to the judges.

15:25.508 --> 15:27.593
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:27.593 --> 15:29.345
<i>- Well, John, you have</i>

15:29.345 --> 15:31.889
<i>the most finished blade</i>
<i>out of anyone here,</i>

15:31.889 --> 15:33.641
but there's a crack right here,

15:33.641 --> 15:35.768
<i>right at the junction</i>
<i>of the tang.</i>

15:35.768 --> 15:37.270
Luckily, it's on
the spine side,

15:37.270 --> 15:38.855
so any heat applied
to that area

15:38.855 --> 15:41.023
wouldn't transfer down
to the blade.

15:41.023 --> 15:43.151
In general, it's a clean
piece of steel.

15:43.151 --> 15:44.986
Well done.
- Thank you.

15:44.986 --> 15:46.904
- Bladesmiths, congratulations.

15:46.904 --> 15:49.657
All of your blades
have made parameters,

15:49.657 --> 15:52.285
and you're moving into
this next round of competition.

15:52.285 --> 15:53.995
Now that your blades
have been tempered,

15:53.995 --> 15:55.705
it's time to turn them into
fully functional weapons

15:55.705 --> 15:57.498
by attaching handles to them.

15:57.498 --> 15:59.625
The only additional stipulation
in this round

15:59.625 --> 16:02.587
is that you add a guard
to your blades.

16:02.587 --> 16:05.756
After the time runs out and
your blades have been tested,

16:05.756 --> 16:07.675
one of you will have to
surrender your weapon

16:07.675 --> 16:10.052
and leave the Forge.

16:10.052 --> 16:11.929
Good luck.
Your three hours starts...

16:11.929 --> 16:13.514
now.

16:13.514 --> 16:15.933
I don't think we've ever
put competitors

16:15.933 --> 16:17.685
through the physical rigors

16:17.685 --> 16:19.312
that we've put
these guys through,

16:19.312 --> 16:21.689
and these guys
rose to the occasion.

16:21.689 --> 16:24.817
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

16:24.817 --> 16:29.238
- My tang is too short,
so I'm making a splice.

16:29.238 --> 16:31.490
And then, I will
cut a piece of metal

16:31.490 --> 16:33.492
to fit in here,
and I will weld it on.

16:33.492 --> 16:35.077
- You put a step in it,
like that.

16:35.077 --> 16:37.205
- Okay.
- Now that weld

16:37.205 --> 16:40.208
is going to be an L shape.
- I got you. I got you.

16:40.208 --> 16:42.293
<i>- This will make</i>
<i>the weld stronger</i>

16:42.293 --> 16:45.213
<i>because I'll have a longer</i>
<i>surface area to weld on.</i>

16:45.213 --> 16:46.881
- Smart work.

16:46.881 --> 16:48.758
- Michael, let's talk
about his blade.

16:48.758 --> 16:50.468
- Well, it's definitely
unfinished.

16:50.468 --> 16:52.762
There's that area where you
can tell it narrows,

16:52.762 --> 16:54.096
and then it widens out again.

16:54.096 --> 16:55.640
That's a weak spot right there

16:55.640 --> 16:57.475
for any kind of
chopping or stabbing.

16:57.475 --> 16:58.935
<i>- There's a lot of things</i>

16:58.935 --> 17:00.895
<i>I need to address</i>
<i>with this blade.</i>

17:00.895 --> 17:02.521
It ain't going to look pretty,

17:02.521 --> 17:04.190
<i>but I'll try to</i>
<i>make it functional.</i>

17:04.190 --> 17:06.150
[whistles]

17:06.150 --> 17:08.069
- I like that
the first thing John did

17:08.069 --> 17:10.780
was to go over to the welding
station and fix the tang.

17:10.780 --> 17:12.740
- There's a crack in my tang,
so I'm going to go

17:12.740 --> 17:14.784
to the welder,
and fill up that crack.

17:14.784 --> 17:17.411
<i>There are some risks.</i>
<i>It could make the blade soft.</i>

17:17.411 --> 17:19.789
<i>So I'm wrapping my blade</i>
<i>with a wet towel,</i>

17:19.789 --> 17:21.999
<i>so when I weld, none of</i>
<i>the heat moves to the blade</i>

17:21.999 --> 17:23.876
and messes with the heat treat
or the temper.

17:23.876 --> 17:25.544
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:25.544 --> 17:27.463
- I got a little
of a warpage in the blade.

17:27.463 --> 17:28.673
Here we go.

17:28.673 --> 17:30.258
<i>Going to have to draw out</i>

17:30.258 --> 17:31.425
<i>the back of the blade</i>
<i>with the torch.</i>

17:31.425 --> 17:33.219
Hopefully, that softens it.

17:33.219 --> 17:34.971
<i>And then, put it on the anvil</i>

17:34.971 --> 17:37.223
<i>and see if I can't</i>
<i>slowly flatten it out.</i>

17:37.223 --> 17:39.392
- What is he
hammering on it for?

17:39.392 --> 17:41.352
Hammering on
a tempered blade is just--

17:41.352 --> 17:44.355
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

17:44.355 --> 17:45.606
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:45.606 --> 17:47.149
- [groans]

17:47.149 --> 17:49.902
- Oh, Michael just
snapped his blade!

17:53.531 --> 17:56.200
- My plan on the anvil
is to flatten out the blade.
<i>- Aw, crap.</i>
<i>I'm done.</i>

17:56.200 --> 17:57.827
<i>Get the kink out of it.</i>

17:57.827 --> 18:00.454
<i>On that last tap--</i>
Oh, [bleep].

18:00.454 --> 18:02.540
<i>I hear something crack.</i>

18:02.540 --> 18:04.250
I pick the blade up,
and it comes apart.

18:04.250 --> 18:05.876
<i>[heavy rock musical flourish]</i>

18:05.876 --> 18:07.962
<i>[tense music]</i>

18:07.962 --> 18:10.673
<i>It's like getting</i>
<i>sucker punched in the gut.</i>

18:10.673 --> 18:12.133
I just kind of froze.

18:12.133 --> 18:13.843
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:13.843 --> 18:15.553
- You can't just stand there
staring at it.

18:15.553 --> 18:16.929
He needs to get to work.
- Yep.

18:16.929 --> 18:18.639
- He needs to
start thinking about

18:18.639 --> 18:19.890
how do you get around this?

18:19.890 --> 18:21.601
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:21.601 --> 18:25.438
- Hey, weld it up.
- Yeah, what the hell?

18:25.438 --> 18:27.815
- Mike is going to the welder.
- Good.

18:27.815 --> 18:31.402
<i>- I can't give up now.</i>
<i>I'm going to weld this blade.</i>

18:31.402 --> 18:34.864
You know, it's better than
turning in a broken blade.

18:34.864 --> 18:37.658
<i>For my handle, I'm going to</i>
<i>go with this linen Micarta.</i>

18:37.658 --> 18:38.784
<i>It looks tough.</i>

18:38.784 --> 18:40.578
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:40.578 --> 18:41.746
I get about halfway down,
I hear the little--

18:41.746 --> 18:42.872
[loud snap]

18:42.872 --> 18:45.791
Oh, no!
It cracked.

18:45.791 --> 18:47.335
- How the hell do you crack
linen Micarta?

18:47.335 --> 18:49.128
- It can be a little brittle.

18:49.128 --> 18:50.546
<i>- I started drilling</i>
<i>on my second material.</i>

18:50.546 --> 18:53.424
I'm getting down,
and then, all of a sudden.

18:53.424 --> 18:55.134
[loud snap]

18:55.134 --> 18:56.510
[groans]

18:56.510 --> 18:58.429
- John, two handle blocks
are down.

18:58.429 --> 19:00.473
What are you doing?

19:00.473 --> 19:03.184
- So it's back to square one,
for the third time.

19:03.184 --> 19:04.685
Now I'm rushing
to beat the clock.

19:04.685 --> 19:07.063
Last time.
Come on, baby.

19:07.063 --> 19:08.856
I have to get this handle on,

19:08.856 --> 19:12.818
<i>so I mix up some epoxy,</i>
<i>put it in the handle.</i>

19:12.818 --> 19:15.154
<i>And, uh--I'm just hoping</i>
<i>for the best.</i>

19:15.154 --> 19:17.657
- Bladesmiths,
90 minutes has elapsed.

19:17.657 --> 19:20.409
You have just 90
tiny little minutes remaining

19:20.409 --> 19:22.119
to finish your work.

19:22.119 --> 19:25.706
- For guard material,
I decided on some brass.

19:25.706 --> 19:27.583
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:27.583 --> 19:29.502
My handle went on real well.

19:29.502 --> 19:32.004
And then, I have
a lot of handle to shape.

19:32.004 --> 19:34.131
- So it looks like
Tim's shaping his handle now.

19:34.131 --> 19:36.300
Is that right?
- Yeah, he's all glued up.

19:36.300 --> 19:38.928
- It's interesting
how fast the tide can turn.

19:38.928 --> 19:41.972
<i>Earlier, nothing's working.</i>

19:41.972 --> 19:45.476
<i>Now, as I grind,</i>
<i>it's just coming out so easy.</i>

19:45.476 --> 19:47.186
That's "Forged in Fire"
for you.

19:47.186 --> 19:50.147
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

19:50.147 --> 19:52.942
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:52.942 --> 19:56.112
- Looks like our man, Mike,
has a blade back in the game.

19:56.112 --> 19:59.657
- Doug, what do you think
about the functionality

19:59.657 --> 20:01.867
of Mike's blade for the test?

20:01.867 --> 20:03.828
- We know that there's
a crack in the blade

20:03.828 --> 20:05.204
that he welded together.

20:05.204 --> 20:06.831
So we don't know
if it's strong.

20:06.831 --> 20:08.749
We know there's
a small section right there

20:08.749 --> 20:10.501
when you're puncturing
that could crack--

20:10.501 --> 20:12.002
you know, it could crack
or break off.

20:12.002 --> 20:13.003
<i>- I'm trying to make</i>
<i>a comeback</i>

20:13.003 --> 20:14.505
<i>from after that crack.</i>

20:14.505 --> 20:16.090
Yeah, it sucked.
It kind of took me back

20:16.090 --> 20:17.591
for a minute.
I had to collect my thoughts.

20:17.591 --> 20:20.344
Think what to do.
But I'm still in the game.

20:20.344 --> 20:22.680
<i>I'm going to drill</i>
<i>this handle out.</i>

20:22.680 --> 20:23.931
<i>- I've always</i>
<i>looked at our pantry</i>

20:23.931 --> 20:25.725
<i>and look at our</i>
<i>natural handles</i>

20:25.725 --> 20:27.393
that always had the horn,
and always wonder why

20:27.393 --> 20:29.437
won't anybody just
use that as a handle?

20:29.437 --> 20:32.606
The whole horn itself.
- The elk antler, it's simple.

20:32.606 --> 20:34.400
<i>Drill your hole in it,</i>
<i>get it set in.</i>

20:34.400 --> 20:36.068
<i>Pin it and glue it,</i>
<i>you're done.</i>

20:36.068 --> 20:37.778
Yeah!
- That's one of the benefits

20:37.778 --> 20:39.321
of grabbing an antler
for a handle.

20:39.321 --> 20:41.031
No shaping.

20:41.031 --> 20:42.533
- I'm not going to
make the blade too pretty,

20:42.533 --> 20:44.744
but it'll work.

20:44.744 --> 20:48.289
<i>- Oh, I'm nervous.</i>
<i>Don't have much time left.</i>

20:48.289 --> 20:51.041
I--I mean, I got to get my
blade sharpened, for sure.

20:51.041 --> 20:54.003
<i>I'd rather have a sharp blade</i>
<i>than a perfect-fitting handle,</i>

20:54.003 --> 20:55.379
<i>so I'm going to</i>
<i>get that blade sharpened,</i>

20:55.379 --> 20:56.756
<i>and with any time left,</i>

20:56.756 --> 20:58.507
I'm going to get
that handle feeling good.

20:58.507 --> 21:00.885
<i>The convex edge</i>
<i>is good for testing</i>

21:00.885 --> 21:03.012
<i>because it doesn't have</i>
<i>as much of a chance</i>

21:03.012 --> 21:05.431
to bend or crack or chip.

21:05.431 --> 21:07.391
It's just more of a tough edge.

21:07.391 --> 21:10.811
<i>The tests are corrugated metal</i>
<i>and a tarp slice.</i>

21:10.811 --> 21:12.313
With the corrugated metal,
I want to leave my tip

21:12.313 --> 21:14.231
thick enough
so I don't have any worries

21:14.231 --> 21:16.484
about breaking when they shove
the corrugated metal.

21:16.484 --> 21:18.778
And I just want to have
a nice, sharp edge

21:18.778 --> 21:20.488
just to make sure
it goes through that tarp.

21:20.488 --> 21:23.532
<i>[tense music]</i>

21:23.532 --> 21:25.659
<i>- So there's two or three</i>
<i>minutes left in the round.</i>

21:25.659 --> 21:27.620
As I'm grinding,
I feel like my tip

21:27.620 --> 21:29.246
might be a little hard.

21:29.246 --> 21:31.457
And if that's stuck through
a piece of metal,

21:31.457 --> 21:36.295
that tip could break right off
and be a catastrophic failure.

21:36.295 --> 21:38.881
- Now, Tim's got a torch out.
What is he doing?

21:38.881 --> 21:41.550
- He's blue backing
just the blade tip

21:41.550 --> 21:43.969
so that it doesn't fail
in a stab test.

21:43.969 --> 21:47.014
- What I'm hoping this'll do
is make that tip springy

21:47.014 --> 21:48.974
<i>and to not be brittle</i>
<i>and break.</i>

21:48.974 --> 21:52.019
<i>The risk of doing this</i>
<i>is then, the tip is too soft,</i>

21:52.019 --> 21:54.772
<i>and it rolls over instead of</i>
<i>punching through the steel.</i>

21:54.772 --> 21:59.944
- Five, four, three, two, one.

21:59.944 --> 22:02.863
Bladesmiths, stop what
you're doing; drop your tools.

22:02.863 --> 22:05.991
This second round
of competition is over.

22:05.991 --> 22:08.035
<i>- I haven't been</i>
<i>making blades that long,</i>

22:08.035 --> 22:09.703
<i>but I don't care how long</i>
<i>I've been doing this.</i>

22:09.703 --> 22:10.830
I mean, I'm in it to win it.

22:10.830 --> 22:12.998
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:12.998 --> 22:15.709
- Bladesmiths, welcome to
the strength test.

22:15.709 --> 22:17.962
To test the strength
and durability of your edge,

22:17.962 --> 22:19.463
as well as the overall
construction of your knives,

22:19.463 --> 22:21.882
I'll be stabbing into
this corrugated steel.

22:21.882 --> 22:24.093
This test is all about what the
steel does to your knives,

22:24.093 --> 22:26.053
and not what your knives
do to the steel.

22:26.053 --> 22:27.513
John, you're up.
You ready?

22:27.513 --> 22:29.139
- Okay.
- Okay.

22:29.139 --> 22:31.141
[laughter]

22:31.141 --> 22:33.060
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

22:33.060 --> 22:34.186
<i>- I'm about to puke.</i>
<i>I mean, my heart's beating</i>

22:34.186 --> 22:36.480
<i>100 miles an hour.</i>

22:36.480 --> 22:39.692
<i>With this handle, all I got is</i>
<i>epoxy holding that together.</i>

22:39.692 --> 22:41.861
That handle could break in half
or slide off.

22:41.861 --> 22:44.822
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:44.822 --> 22:47.825
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

22:47.825 --> 22:54.748
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:58.168 --> 23:00.421
[exhales]

23:00.421 --> 23:02.464
- Well, John,
first things first.

23:02.464 --> 23:04.258
Your blade is all in one piece.

23:04.258 --> 23:06.260
In this challenge,
that's not a given.

23:06.260 --> 23:10.472
Your edge took some rolling
kind of the whole way down.

23:10.472 --> 23:12.182
<i>[tense music]</i>

23:12.182 --> 23:13.642
Your point held up really well.

23:13.642 --> 23:17.062
Your handle is blocky.

23:17.062 --> 23:19.440
It still has
some corners to it.

23:19.440 --> 23:21.358
But at the same time,
it's comfortable.

23:21.358 --> 23:23.611
So well done.
- Thank you.

23:23.611 --> 23:24.737
- Tim, you're up next.
You ready?

23:24.737 --> 23:26.780
- I'm ready.
- Yeah, good.

23:26.780 --> 23:28.449
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

23:28.449 --> 23:30.242
<i>- My heart's beating</i>
<i>like crazy.</i>

23:30.242 --> 23:33.370
<i>The tip of my knife</i>
<i>felt a little hard to me.</i>

23:33.370 --> 23:34.997
<i>So if the tip breaks off,</i>

23:34.997 --> 23:36.874
<i>if it rolls over</i>
<i>and doesn't go through,</i>

23:36.874 --> 23:39.668
both of those things
could be sending me home.

23:39.668 --> 23:42.671
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

23:42.671 --> 23:49.553
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:00.230 --> 24:02.816
- Well, Tim, let's talk about
your edge first.

24:02.816 --> 24:05.569
It's still pretty sharp,

24:05.569 --> 24:08.572
but it took
a little rolling here.

24:08.572 --> 24:12.034
The tip is pretty flat
right here.

24:12.034 --> 24:14.203
Other than those two things,

24:14.203 --> 24:15.704
it's certainly
all in one piece.

24:15.704 --> 24:17.539
It's still straight.
Really well done.

24:17.539 --> 24:19.041
- Thank you very much.
- Mike, you're up.

24:19.041 --> 24:20.459
Are you ready?
- Yes, sir.

24:20.459 --> 24:21.835
- All right.

24:21.835 --> 24:24.046
<i>- I'm feeling nervous.</i>

24:24.046 --> 24:27.216
<i>I'm thinking it's going</i>
<i>to break again.</i>

24:27.216 --> 24:30.344
<i>I got to remind myself</i>
<i>to breathe,</i>

24:30.344 --> 24:32.589
because if I don't,
I'm going to pass out.

24:35.779 --> 24:39.770
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

24:39.770 --> 24:42.731
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

24:42.731 --> 24:49.655
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:57.871 --> 24:59.581
- [exhales]

24:59.581 --> 25:01.917
- Well, Mike, wow.
- Yeah.

25:01.917 --> 25:04.044
Uh, you can say that.

25:04.044 --> 25:06.630
- There's a
tiny little deflection

25:06.630 --> 25:09.341
on the edge right here,
but even where

25:09.341 --> 25:12.928
the MIG weld was,
the edge looks good.

25:12.928 --> 25:16.015
The handle is a little
on the small side,

25:16.015 --> 25:17.433
but still comfortable.

25:17.433 --> 25:19.101
I could hold onto it
really well.

25:19.101 --> 25:21.228
In all, I'm impressed.
Well done.

25:21.228 --> 25:22.396
- Thank you.

25:22.396 --> 25:24.314
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

25:24.314 --> 25:27.943
- All right, bladesmiths.
This is the sharpness test.

25:27.943 --> 25:29.778
To find out how sharp
your weapons are,

25:29.778 --> 25:32.448
I'll take your weapon
and slice and dice

25:32.448 --> 25:34.241
through these tarps.

25:34.241 --> 25:36.618
Now, unlike the strength test,
this is all about

25:36.618 --> 25:39.455
what your edge
will do to the tarp.

25:39.455 --> 25:40.789
John, you're up first.
You ready?

25:40.789 --> 25:43.208
- Yeah, let's do it.
- Let's do this.

25:43.208 --> 25:45.210
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

25:45.210 --> 25:46.879
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:46.879 --> 25:49.006
[laughter]

25:49.006 --> 25:51.967
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

25:51.967 --> 25:58.891
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:06.482 --> 26:08.400
All right, John.
So about your blade here.

26:08.400 --> 26:11.070
Sharp.
What can I say?

26:11.070 --> 26:13.489
On the stabbing,
it glides easily on the tarp.

26:13.489 --> 26:16.658
And on the chop there,
it cuts nicely.

26:16.658 --> 26:19.203
Overall, sir,
your knife will cut.

26:19.203 --> 26:20.704
- Thank you.

26:20.704 --> 26:23.123
- Tim, you're up next.
Are you ready?

26:23.123 --> 26:25.375
- I'm ready.
- Let's do this.

26:25.375 --> 26:28.337
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

26:28.337 --> 26:31.215
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:31.215 --> 26:34.134
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

26:34.134 --> 26:41.058
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:50.192 --> 26:53.529
All right, Tim.
The handle, very comfortable.

26:53.529 --> 26:55.906
Now, your edge.

26:55.906 --> 26:59.701
In the slash, it did not
penetrate the tarp.

26:59.701 --> 27:01.495
But, you know what,
with some force,

27:01.495 --> 27:04.748
it does puncture, and it
lacerates all the way down.

27:04.748 --> 27:07.334
Overall, your weapon,
sir, it will cut.

27:07.334 --> 27:09.002
- Thank you.
- All right, Michael.

27:09.002 --> 27:10.379
Your turn.
You ready?

27:10.379 --> 27:12.464
- Ready as I'll ever be.
- Let's do this.

27:12.464 --> 27:15.425
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

27:15.425 --> 27:17.302
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:17.302 --> 27:19.429
- Here we go.

27:19.429 --> 27:22.349
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

27:22.349 --> 27:29.314
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:39.908 --> 27:41.285
Ooh, wow.
- All right, Mike.

27:41.285 --> 27:43.161
Let's talk about
your blade here.

27:43.161 --> 27:46.206
You have an acute tip that
punctures well and slashes,

27:46.206 --> 27:48.083
but because of the puncturing
all the way through,

27:48.083 --> 27:50.627
your ricasso right here
got hung up a couple of times.

27:50.627 --> 27:52.254
But when we
go back to the edge,

27:52.254 --> 27:55.173
as you can see,
it cuts this tarp.

27:55.173 --> 27:58.719
Overall, sir,
your blade, it will cut.

27:58.719 --> 28:00.262
- Yeah.

28:00.262 --> 28:02.222
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

28:02.222 --> 28:04.600
- Gentleman, the judges'
deliberation is complete.

28:04.600 --> 28:06.184
It's time for
one of you bladesmiths

28:06.184 --> 28:07.394
to leave the Forge.

28:07.394 --> 28:11.315
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:11.315 --> 28:13.859
Tim, your blade
didn't make the cut.

28:13.859 --> 28:16.528
- Tim, by softening
the tip of your blade,

28:16.528 --> 28:18.614
you took damage
in that steel stab,

28:18.614 --> 28:21.241
and that affected your cutting
ability in the sharpness test.

28:21.241 --> 28:22.910
That's why we're
letting you go.

28:22.910 --> 28:24.870
- I understand.
- Please surrender your blade.

28:24.870 --> 28:26.622
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:26.622 --> 28:28.123
<i>- I'm not coming home</i>
<i>with the win,</i>

28:28.123 --> 28:29.958
but I'm coming home
with some great friends,

28:29.958 --> 28:31.043
a great experience...

28:31.043 --> 28:32.794
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:32.794 --> 28:36.590
And seeing how far I can
be pushed in a challenge.

28:36.590 --> 28:38.550
<i>Knife-making</i>
<i>is such a fun thing,</i>

28:38.550 --> 28:40.302
and it's exciting to be a part

28:40.302 --> 28:42.304
of helping other people
to understand this craft.

28:42.304 --> 28:46.558
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:46.558 --> 28:49.102
- John, Mike, congratulations.
You've both made it into

28:49.102 --> 28:50.812
the final round
of this competition.

28:50.812 --> 28:52.731
Now, we're sending you back
to your home forges,

28:52.731 --> 28:56.234
to re-create an
iconic weapon from history.

28:56.234 --> 28:58.153
That weapon is...

28:58.153 --> 29:01.323
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

29:01.323 --> 29:03.241
The bardiche.

29:04.576 --> 29:07.120
- Sweet.

29:07.120 --> 29:09.706
<i>- Vicious and menacing,</i>
<i>the bardiche was a favorite</i>

29:09.706 --> 29:11.708
<i>of Eastern European</i>
<i>infantry soldiers</i>

29:11.708 --> 29:14.169
<i>during the 16th</i>
<i>and 17th centuries.</i>

29:14.169 --> 29:16.171
<i>Its large,</i>
<i>crescent-shaped axe head</i>

29:16.171 --> 29:18.006
<i>measured nearly two feet</i>
<i>at the edge</i>

29:18.006 --> 29:19.967
<i>and could cleave through</i>
<i>flesh and bone.</i>

29:19.967 --> 29:22.552
<i>Specialized soldiers</i>
<i>called streltsy</i>

29:22.552 --> 29:24.930
<i>would use the bardiche's pole</i>
<i>to balance their muskets</i>

29:24.930 --> 29:26.682
<i>for firing from a distance,</i>

29:26.682 --> 29:29.142
<i>then switch to their axe</i>
<i>during melee combat.</i>

29:29.142 --> 29:30.978
<i>Though rare</i>
<i>in American pop culture,</i>

29:30.978 --> 29:33.230
<i>you can experience</i>
<i>the bardiche's savagery</i>

29:33.230 --> 29:34.815
<i>on the virtual battlefield</i>
<i>in the game</i>

29:34.815 --> 29:36.775
<i>"Chivalry: Medieval Warfare."</i>

29:36.775 --> 29:40.862
- Um, I've never really made
anything exactly like this,

29:40.862 --> 29:42.030
<i>so I'm real excited,</i>
<i>because now,</i>

29:42.030 --> 29:43.573
<i>I got a little bit more time.</i>

29:43.573 --> 29:46.201
I can really showcase
my artistic side,

29:46.201 --> 29:48.161
and really show what I can do.

29:48.161 --> 29:50.831
- Your weapons must fall within
the following parameters.

29:50.831 --> 29:53.583
First, you must have
a sharpened, perforated blade

29:53.583 --> 29:56.628
that is between
19 and 22 inches in length,

29:56.628 --> 29:58.296
and the length of your shaft

29:58.296 --> 30:01.925
must be between
56 and 58 inches.

30:01.925 --> 30:03.844
You will have five days
at your home forges

30:03.844 --> 30:05.554
in which to complete
this challenge.

30:05.554 --> 30:07.431
At the end of those five days,
you will return

30:07.431 --> 30:10.517
and present your bardiches
to our panel of expert judges,

30:10.517 --> 30:13.562
and only after they've
chopped, sliced,

30:13.562 --> 30:16.023
and killed their way
through those tests

30:16.023 --> 30:18.567
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

30:18.567 --> 30:22.237
who also leaves here
with a check for $10,000.

30:22.237 --> 30:24.740
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in five days.

30:24.740 --> 30:26.700
- All right.
- Let's do this.

30:26.700 --> 30:28.702
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

30:28.702 --> 30:30.746
<i>- Day one, I need to make sure</i>
<i>I'm going to win,</i>

30:30.746 --> 30:35.042
<i>so I'm going to make this</i>
<i>a fully functional bardiche.</i>

30:35.042 --> 30:37.294
Oh, yeah, now we got
a good fire.

30:37.294 --> 30:39.796
<i>I use a coke forge because</i>
<i>it's what I grew up on.</i>

30:39.796 --> 30:41.298
<i>I'm using 5160.</i>

30:41.298 --> 30:43.717
There we go.

30:43.717 --> 30:44.885
Heads up.

30:44.885 --> 30:46.428
[hammer thunking]

30:46.428 --> 30:49.014
Oh, that's a beautiful sound,
ain't it?

30:49.014 --> 30:51.641
<i>I'm really struggling</i>
<i>keeping the blade straight.</i>

30:51.641 --> 30:53.351
<i>The blade is curving</i>
<i>right when I'm forging</i>

30:53.351 --> 30:54.936
<i>the edge of the blade.</i>

30:54.936 --> 30:56.313
If you can't get it straight
before grinding,

30:56.313 --> 30:58.148
you just as well start over.

30:58.148 --> 31:00.484
<i>Having to keep the blade</i>
<i>being straight</i>

31:00.484 --> 31:02.527
<i>throughout the forging process</i>
<i>is putting me behind</i>

31:02.527 --> 31:04.321
<i>because I can't move</i>
<i>with the blade</i>

31:04.321 --> 31:06.448
<i>as fast as I need to.</i>

31:06.448 --> 31:07.657
Oof, she's crooked.

31:07.657 --> 31:10.827
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

31:10.827 --> 31:13.830
- Back home, getting ready
to start on this bardiche.

31:13.830 --> 31:16.708
<i>5160 is the metal</i>
<i>I'm going to be using.</i>

31:16.708 --> 31:19.711
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:19.711 --> 31:22.005
<i>My goal is to get</i>
<i>the rough shape and stuff</i>

31:22.005 --> 31:24.341
knocked out as fast as I can,
because I would really like to

31:24.341 --> 31:27.135
spend as much time as possible
really showing my creativeness.

31:27.135 --> 31:29.179
<i>I'm going to try to</i>
<i>just focus on the blade,</i>

31:29.179 --> 31:31.681
<i>because this is the most</i>
<i>important part of my build.</i>

31:31.681 --> 31:33.266
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:33.266 --> 31:35.644
End of day one,
ready to call it a night.

31:35.644 --> 31:37.479
I'm going to
put it in the forge

31:37.479 --> 31:40.315
and turn off the forge
when I come back tomorrow.

31:40.315 --> 31:42.025
It's going to leave
this material nice and soft,

31:42.025 --> 31:44.569
so I can drill my holes,
I can grind,

31:44.569 --> 31:46.696
and all of this material's
going to be a lot softer

31:46.696 --> 31:48.281
than if I just
let it dry real quick

31:48.281 --> 31:50.867
right here in the air, so.

31:50.867 --> 31:52.202
That's it.

31:52.202 --> 31:54.704
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:54.704 --> 31:57.499
<i>- Day two,</i>
<i>move on to the handle.</i>

31:57.499 --> 32:00.710
I'm going to start shaping
down here, leave less here.

32:00.710 --> 32:03.171
<i>Turn on the grinder,</i>
<i>got a belt on there.</i>

32:03.171 --> 32:04.381
<i>As soon as it gets going--</i>

32:04.381 --> 32:06.007
[grunts]

32:06.007 --> 32:09.052
Snaps, hits me right
in the chest. Ouch.

32:09.052 --> 32:12.264
The blade's going to go here,
so you want more mass here.

32:12.264 --> 32:13.807
You want it tapered down here,

32:13.807 --> 32:15.100
because you're
going to hold it.

32:15.100 --> 32:17.227
So you can be able to swing it.

32:17.227 --> 32:20.021
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

32:20.021 --> 32:21.523
<i>These holes</i>
<i>in the bardiche blade</i>

32:21.523 --> 32:23.900
<i>make the blade</i>
<i>a little lighter.</i>

32:23.900 --> 32:29.364
Okay, got all the holes drilled
all the way through.

32:29.364 --> 32:31.992
Yeah, looks pretty cool,
I think.

32:31.992 --> 32:34.077
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

32:34.077 --> 32:35.579
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:35.579 --> 32:36.830
- And that,
ladies and gentleman,

32:36.830 --> 32:38.707
is my last hole.

32:38.707 --> 32:42.252
My goals today, I have to
get the blade heat treated.

32:42.252 --> 32:44.421
<i>I don't got</i>
<i>a quench tank big enough,</i>

32:44.421 --> 32:46.715
<i>so I had to fabricate</i>
<i>a quench tank.</i>

32:46.715 --> 32:48.216
And we'll see
if it holds liquid,

32:48.216 --> 32:50.302
so I know if I can
fill it with my oil.

32:50.302 --> 32:52.554
Got some leaks.

32:52.554 --> 32:54.181
<i>And I might</i>
<i>put some plastic in it,</i>

32:54.181 --> 32:56.266
<i>and maybe line it with tinfoil</i>

32:56.266 --> 32:58.643
<i>to try to keep the heat</i>
<i>away from the plastic.</i>

32:58.643 --> 33:00.312
You may be wondering
what's going to happen

33:00.312 --> 33:03.064
when the oil
gets hot inside there,

33:03.064 --> 33:05.650
and I may be wondering
the same thing.

33:05.650 --> 33:07.277
<i>Now, I'm going to stick</i>
<i>my blade in the forge</i>

33:07.277 --> 33:09.237
<i>and normalize it a few times,</i>

33:09.237 --> 33:11.531
<i>and then, I'm going to go in</i>
<i>for my heat treat.</i>

33:11.531 --> 33:13.533
I just hope
this thing holds up.

33:13.533 --> 33:14.949
Oh!

33:17.329 --> 33:19.331
<i>- So I got my metal</i>
<i>in the quench tank.</i>

33:19.331 --> 33:21.666
<i>It's flaming up.</i>
<i>I'm more worried about</i>

33:21.666 --> 33:23.376
<i>listening for cracks</i>
<i>or anything than I am</i>

33:23.376 --> 33:25.587
about burning
my shop down at the moment.

33:25.587 --> 33:27.714
<i>Then, my oil</i>
<i>starts leaking out.</i>

33:27.714 --> 33:29.424
There's all my oil!

33:29.424 --> 33:31.092
[exhales]

33:31.092 --> 33:33.428
<i>So I decided to</i>
<i>take the blade out,</i>

33:33.428 --> 33:35.013
but I think I got a hard blade.

33:35.013 --> 33:37.432
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:37.432 --> 33:39.184
<i>- Day four, I'm feeling</i>

33:39.184 --> 33:40.727
<i>a little nervous</i>
<i>about the heat treat.</i>

33:40.727 --> 33:42.854
All right,
the moment of truth.

33:42.854 --> 33:45.565
Lord, let this go well.

33:45.565 --> 33:49.027
<i>I'm edge quenching, hoping for</i>
<i>a hard edge and a soft spine,</i>

33:49.027 --> 33:51.446
<i>therefore reinforcing</i>
<i>the blade.</i>

33:51.446 --> 33:53.281
<i>[upbeat rock music]</i>

33:53.281 --> 33:54.616
Here we go.

33:54.616 --> 34:01.581
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:01.581 --> 34:03.959
File test.

34:03.959 --> 34:07.128
Oh, yeah, we got her.
Yeah!

34:07.128 --> 34:08.838
Everything's ready
to put together.

34:08.838 --> 34:11.174
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:11.174 --> 34:13.260
I have a little concern
about the weight.

34:13.260 --> 34:14.552
[grunts]
Just do like--

34:14.552 --> 34:15.637
[exhales]

34:15.637 --> 34:17.973
Like that.

34:17.973 --> 34:19.975
<i>It's a little bit front heavy.</i>
<i>It does bother me a little.</i>

34:19.975 --> 34:23.061
But at this point,
not much I can do about it.

34:23.061 --> 34:24.729
<i>- So today, hopefully</i>
<i>I get to start on</i>

34:24.729 --> 34:26.731
<i>all the little detail work</i>
<i>on the blade,</i>

34:26.731 --> 34:28.316
and that's really
what I've been waiting for

34:28.316 --> 34:30.443
for over three days.

34:30.443 --> 34:32.237
<i>I'm going to try</i>
<i>to incorporate</i>

34:32.237 --> 34:34.906
<i>maybe like, a dragon-type</i>
<i>thing on one side,</i>

34:34.906 --> 34:38.535
<i>and maybe a bunch of</i>
<i>just design on the other.</i>

34:38.535 --> 34:41.204
<i>This will be</i>
<i>the most detailed blade</i>

34:41.204 --> 34:42.580
<i>I've probably ever made.</i>

34:42.580 --> 34:44.082
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:44.082 --> 34:45.959
<i>So then,</i>
<i>I'll put that in acid,</i>

34:45.959 --> 34:49.379
<i>and it'll eat away everywhere</i>
<i>besides the paint.</i>

34:49.379 --> 34:52.257
And then, after that,
I'll wipe off all the paint,

34:52.257 --> 34:55.093
and you should get
a nice, shiny finish

34:55.093 --> 34:57.178
<i>from where the paint was,</i>
<i>and then,</i>

34:57.178 --> 35:00.473
<i>kind of a rustic patina'd look</i>
<i>on the rest of the blade.</i>

35:00.473 --> 35:01.933
So it's just
one big piece of art

35:01.933 --> 35:03.435
<i>as well as a weapon.</i>

35:03.435 --> 35:06.354
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

35:06.354 --> 35:08.231
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:08.231 --> 35:10.358
- John and Michael,
welcome back to the Forge.

35:10.358 --> 35:12.360
It's been a long journey
for you both,

35:12.360 --> 35:13.820
and for your weapons,

35:13.820 --> 35:16.114
but now that
your bardiches are here,

35:16.114 --> 35:18.241
it's time to test them
to determine which of you

35:18.241 --> 35:20.368
is our next
"Forged in Fire" champion.

35:20.368 --> 35:22.704
John, tell us about your blade.

35:22.704 --> 35:24.456
- I used 5160 for the blade.

35:24.456 --> 35:25.749
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:25.749 --> 35:27.417
<i>I used hickory on the handle,</i>

35:27.417 --> 35:29.419
<i>got it all wedged in;</i>
<i>a brass pin.</i>

35:29.419 --> 35:30.420
- How about you, Mike?
Tell us about your blade.

35:30.420 --> 35:32.213
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:32.213 --> 35:34.299
<i>- I used 5160</i>
<i>as well for the blade.</i>

35:34.299 --> 35:37.385
<i>The neck and the socket</i>
<i>is made from mild steel.</i>

35:37.385 --> 35:40.013
Yeah, I believe it's going
to hold up well.

35:40.013 --> 35:43.933
- Well, I hope you made them
strong, sharp, and deadly.

35:43.933 --> 35:45.435
Doug?

35:45.435 --> 35:47.562
<i>[tense music]</i>

35:47.562 --> 35:50.940
- All right, bladesmiths.
This is the kill test.

35:50.940 --> 35:53.318
To find out how lethal
your weapon is,

35:53.318 --> 35:55.528
I will take your bardiche
and deliver lethal chops

35:55.528 --> 35:57.781
on this pig carcass.

35:57.781 --> 35:58.948
John, you're up first.
Are you ready?

35:58.948 --> 36:01.368
- Let's do it.
- Let's do this.

36:01.368 --> 36:03.912
- Going into the kill test,
I feel pretty good.

36:03.912 --> 36:07.040
<i>What I'm really hoping for</i>
<i>is Doug's going to say</i>

36:07.040 --> 36:08.833
<i>"It will kill."</i>

36:08.833 --> 36:11.169
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:11.169 --> 36:14.130
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

36:14.130 --> 36:15.965
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:15.965 --> 36:16.925
- Nice.

36:16.925 --> 36:23.807
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:26.226 --> 36:28.019
- Nice.
Right on, brother.

36:28.019 --> 36:30.021
- [exhales]

36:30.021 --> 36:32.107
- All right, John, let's talk
about your bardiche here.

36:32.107 --> 36:33.983
I love the swells.

36:33.983 --> 36:35.902
By putting these swells
right there,

36:35.902 --> 36:38.780
it allows me to adjust my hand,
and get a good grip

36:38.780 --> 36:40.699
every time I move it around.

36:40.699 --> 36:43.785
Your blade right here
is razor sharp.

36:43.785 --> 36:47.205
It cuts through spine, bones,
and thick flesh.

36:47.205 --> 36:50.792
Overall, sir,
your bardiche will kill.

36:50.792 --> 36:51.918
- I got something to show you.
- Oh, sure.

36:51.918 --> 36:54.754
- Kill test?

36:54.754 --> 36:55.880
- Oh, "It will kill!"

36:55.880 --> 36:57.590
[laughter]

36:57.590 --> 36:59.342
Good job.
- I was hoping to kill,

36:59.342 --> 37:00.885
because I had to do that.

37:00.885 --> 37:02.303
- Right on.
- Good job.

37:02.303 --> 37:03.930
- All right,
Michael, your turn.

37:03.930 --> 37:05.348
You got anything to show me?
- Nope.

37:05.348 --> 37:06.808
- All right,
you ready for this?

37:06.808 --> 37:08.309
- Yes, sir.
- Let's do this.

37:08.309 --> 37:11.354
<i>[tense music]</i>

37:11.354 --> 37:14.357
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

37:14.357 --> 37:16.901
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:16.901 --> 37:18.236
- Nice.

37:18.236 --> 37:22.240
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:22.240 --> 37:24.409
- [panting]

37:24.409 --> 37:25.368
- [exhales]

37:25.368 --> 37:29.497
♪ ♪

37:29.497 --> 37:31.583
[laughter]

37:34.169 --> 37:37.589
<i>[tense music]</i>

37:37.589 --> 37:39.007
- All right, Michael.

37:39.007 --> 37:41.217
This is at least around
11 pounds.

37:41.217 --> 37:43.470
All forward weight.

37:43.470 --> 37:46.097
I waste so much energy
in recoiling

37:46.097 --> 37:47.974
that could be used in attack.

37:47.974 --> 37:51.186
But overall, sir,
your bardiche will kill.

37:51.186 --> 37:52.437
- Yeah!

37:52.437 --> 37:54.355
[grunts]

37:54.355 --> 37:57.233
<i>[tense music]</i>

37:57.233 --> 37:59.235
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to the strength test:

37:59.235 --> 38:02.655
The stump thump
and steer smash.

38:02.655 --> 38:04.908
To test the strength and
durability of your bardiches

38:04.908 --> 38:06.868
as well as their
overall construction,

38:06.868 --> 38:08.912
I'll be chopping mercilessly
into these logs

38:08.912 --> 38:11.164
and cleaving that steer skull
in half.

38:11.164 --> 38:13.500
Remember, this is all about
what happens to your bardiche,

38:13.500 --> 38:14.793
and not what happens
to the wood and bone.

38:14.793 --> 38:16.169
John, you're up first.

38:16.169 --> 38:18.630
You ready?
- Let's do it.

38:18.630 --> 38:21.591
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

38:21.591 --> 38:28.473
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:29.224 --> 38:30.767
- Nice!

38:36.898 --> 38:39.025
Awesome.

38:39.025 --> 38:43.029
- Well, John, your bardiche,
it's got a nice weight to it.

38:43.029 --> 38:46.074
Not a huge fan of these
undulations in the handle,

38:46.074 --> 38:49.661
because I want to be able to
move my hands around.

38:49.661 --> 38:51.955
I'm looking at the edge.
It held up beautifully.

38:51.955 --> 38:53.790
Everything is still
straight and tight.

38:53.790 --> 38:55.625
Good job.
- Thank you.

38:55.625 --> 38:57.335
- Michael, you're up next.
Are you ready?

38:57.335 --> 38:59.003
- Oh, yeah, oh, yeah.
Hope you ate your Wheaties.

38:59.003 --> 39:00.588
- All right.

39:00.588 --> 39:01.965
<i>[tense music]</i>

39:01.965 --> 39:03.216
- Oh, boy.

39:03.216 --> 39:08.179
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:08.179 --> 39:11.099
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

39:11.099 --> 39:15.812
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:15.812 --> 39:17.313
All right.

39:17.313 --> 39:22.652
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:22.652 --> 39:24.320
[laughs]

39:28.116 --> 39:30.159
Ooh.

39:30.159 --> 39:32.370
- Well, Michael,
first things first.

39:32.370 --> 39:34.372
This thing is heavy.
- It's a beast.

39:34.372 --> 39:36.833
- But everything
is still tight.

39:36.833 --> 39:39.669
There's no motion in it,
even after all of that chopping

39:39.669 --> 39:41.588
and smashing of skulls.

39:41.588 --> 39:43.715
The edge held up really well,
so well done.

39:43.715 --> 39:45.091
- That's awesome.
Yeah.

39:45.091 --> 39:46.426
- Up next is
the sharpness test,

39:46.426 --> 39:47.385
and for that,
I give you to Dave.

39:47.385 --> 39:49.345
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:49.345 --> 39:51.931
- All right, gentleman.
Now, unlike the strength test,

39:51.931 --> 39:54.142
this is all about what
your blades do to the target.

39:54.142 --> 39:56.060
So I'm taking one shot
right down the middle,

39:56.060 --> 39:57.687
trying to split
those watermelon,

39:57.687 --> 39:59.939
put half in one bucket
half in the other.

39:59.939 --> 40:01.190
All right, John,
are you ready?

40:01.190 --> 40:02.692
- Let's do it.
- Okay.

40:02.692 --> 40:04.694
<i>[rock music]</i>

40:04.694 --> 40:06.029
<i>- Going into</i>
<i>the sharpness test,</i>

40:06.029 --> 40:07.739
<i>mine's so light.</i>

40:07.739 --> 40:09.240
You know, it can deflect
and go different ways,

40:09.240 --> 40:11.075
<i>so I'm nervous as all get-out.</i>

40:11.075 --> 40:12.240
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:19.792 --> 40:21.252
- Nice.

40:21.252 --> 40:23.880
<i>[tense music]</i>

40:23.880 --> 40:25.715
- All right, John.
It feels good.

40:25.715 --> 40:27.008
It's got a good balance to it.

40:27.008 --> 40:28.593
The shape of this
is really nice.

40:28.593 --> 40:30.637
The cutting edge,
curved like that,

40:30.637 --> 40:32.805
cut through
the watermelon beautifully.

40:32.805 --> 40:34.474
Sharp weapon, nicely done.
- Thank you, thanks.

40:34.474 --> 40:35.934
- All right, Michael,
you're up.

40:35.934 --> 40:37.101
- Are you ready?
- Bring out the beast.

40:37.101 --> 40:38.436
- Okay.

40:38.436 --> 40:41.439
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

40:41.439 --> 40:45.610
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:45.610 --> 40:47.862
- Oh-ho-ho!

40:51.240 --> 40:53.451
- Well, right off,
it's definitely sharp.

40:53.451 --> 40:55.119
But it weighs a ton.

40:55.119 --> 40:58.456
I like the design of this,
but "build strong"

40:58.456 --> 41:00.041
doesn't necessarily mean
"build heavy."

41:00.041 --> 41:02.418
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:02.418 --> 41:06.047
- John, Mike,
you bladesmiths have engaged

41:06.047 --> 41:08.675
in one of our most
difficult competitions.

41:08.675 --> 41:11.803
However, only one of you can be
the "Forged in Fire" champion.

41:11.803 --> 41:13.763
And that champion is...

41:13.763 --> 41:16.724
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

41:16.724 --> 41:18.393
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:18.393 --> 41:20.186
John, congratulations.
- Thank you.

41:20.186 --> 41:22.021
- You're our new
"Forged in Fire" champion.

41:22.021 --> 41:25.274
Mike, unfortunately, your
weapon didn't make the cut.

41:25.274 --> 41:27.652
David Baker's
going to tell you why.

41:27.652 --> 41:29.779
- Mike, you brought us
a weapon that's got

41:29.779 --> 41:31.656
a lot of artistry
that went into it.

41:31.656 --> 41:33.491
But in the end,
it just has so much weight

41:33.491 --> 41:35.493
that it wasn't
an effective bardiche.

41:35.493 --> 41:36.577
That's why we're
letting you go.

41:36.577 --> 41:37.996
- All right.
- Mike.

41:37.996 --> 41:39.205
Please surrender your weapon.

41:39.205 --> 41:41.499
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:41.499 --> 41:43.960
- My experience here
was definitely a challenge.

41:43.960 --> 41:46.504
Pushed me to my limits.
I learned a lot.

41:46.504 --> 41:48.715
<i>I might not be the</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire" champion,</i>

41:48.715 --> 41:51.175
<i>but I still feel like</i>
<i>I'm walking away a winner</i>

41:51.175 --> 41:53.428
because I took on
the challenge for myself,

41:53.428 --> 41:54.804
and I come out a winner.

41:54.804 --> 41:56.764
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:56.764 --> 41:58.349
- John, congratulations.

41:58.349 --> 42:00.893
You're the new
"Forged in Fire" champion,

42:00.893 --> 42:02.353
and that is a title that comes

42:02.353 --> 42:05.273
with a check for how much?
- 10 grand.

42:05.273 --> 42:08.735
- Please present
your bardiche to the judges.

42:08.735 --> 42:11.487
<i>- This is the</i>
<i>most mentally, physically,</i>

42:11.487 --> 42:13.906
<i>emotionally stressful time,</i>

42:13.906 --> 42:15.700
<i>but also the</i>
<i>best time of my life.</i>

42:15.700 --> 42:17.076
Whoo,
"Forged in Fire" champion!

42:17.076 --> 42:18.703
<i>I'm super excited to get home</i>

42:18.703 --> 42:19.871
<i>and tell my wife</i>
<i>about the great news.</i>

42:19.871 --> 42:21.456
<i>Now, the next thing coming up,</i>

42:21.456 --> 42:23.166
<i>I'm going to be having</i>
<i>a baby boy.</i>

42:23.166 --> 42:26.377
So, I mean, this is
a wonderful year, thank God.

42:26.377 --> 42:29.380
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

42:29.380 --> 42:32.759
<i>♪ ♪</i>
